# System Architecture
The OSI Model

The OSI Model means Open Systems Interconnection. It is a model with 7 layers that explains how data moves from one device to another. It is mostly used for learning because real networks do not use it directly.

The 7 Layers

Application - Where users use apps like browsers and email.
Presentation - Changes data format and does encryption.
Session - Starts and ends communication.
Transport - Sends data using TCP or UDP.
Network - Uses IP addresses to send data.
Data Link - Uses MAC addresses and prepares data.
Physical - Sends data through cables or wireless signals.

Why OSI is not used in real life

The OSI model is only for learning. Real networks use the TCP/IP model because it is simpler and works better.

TCP/IP Model

The TCP/IP model has 4 layers:

Application - Works with apps like HTTP, DNS and FTP.
Transport - Uses TCP and UDP.
Internet - Handles IP addresses and routing.
Network Access - Sends data through the network hardware.

System Architecture

What happens when you click your mouse

1.You click the mouse or press a key.
2.The device sends a signal to the computer.
3.The CPU tells the kernel to handle the signal.
4.The kernel sends it to the correct program.
5.The CPU loads the program that needs to respond.
6.The MMU finds the data in RAM.
7.The CPU runs the Fetch, Decode and Execute cycle.
8.The application processes the action.
9.The GPU draws the new screen.
10.The monitor shows the result.

Addressing Modes

Immediate - Data is inside the instruction.
Direct - Data is at a fixed memory address.
Register - Data is in a CPU register.
Indirect - The instruction points to the data.
